{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584690"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:54:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:54:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14773"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67871"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5154"},{"type":"tags","id":"10090"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22724"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67871"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERetinoids are a class of compounds derived from vitamin A that have important therapeutic applications in dermatology. For example, they can be used in the treatment of psoriasis (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the use of retinoids is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They have no effect on immune function","Sebum production is increased","Keratinocyte proliferation is decreased","They are safe to use during pregnancy","Comedone formation is promoted"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERetinoids are vitamin A derivatives with multiple effects on skin cells and function. \u003Cstrong\u003ERetinoids decrease keratinocyte proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E while promoting their differentiation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetinoids\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Edo modulate immune responses and have anti-inflammatory properties; therefore, the statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinoids have no effect on immune function \u003C/strong\u003Eis incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetinoids decrease rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease sebum production\u003C/strong\u003E, which is one of their main therapeutic benefits in acne treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERetinoids are highly teratogenic and absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy (therefore are NOT \u003Cstrong\u003Esafe to use during pregnancy)\u003C/strong\u003E. Women of childbearing age must use effective contraception before, during and after retinoid therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E The statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinoids promote comedone formation\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect - they help prevent and treat comedones by normalising follicular keratinisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Retinoids are derivatives of vitamin A that regulate cell growth, differentiation, and immune function","Isotretinoin reduces sebum production and is effective for severe acne","Teratogenicity is a major risk of retinoid therapy requiring strict contraception"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14773"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21293"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21293"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fxWrHGjOfKRuJxXJjptN8C8IpQQfzI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fxWrHGjOfKRuJxXJjptN8C8IpQQfzI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53336"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T15:43:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T15:44:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67871"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i